Their mixologist is quite gifted and very knowledgeable with the ability to whip up complex concoctions on the fly; she is also, if it is important to you, incredibly attractive.

They offer two tasting menus--a short but still fairly elaborate one and an extravagant 10-course tasting (though much more when you add in all of their many bonus mini courses).  Their 10-course tasting reveals one excellent course after another as well as so many premium ingredients including lobster, truffle, dry-aged rib cap, and foie gras.
Their canapés service is among the best I have experienced--not just in quantity and variety but also quality. Lots of great flavor and texture combinations as well as only one or two slight misses.

Though the head chef has been here over 10 years, the food feels very contemporary and reminds me of some of America's best restaurants--extravagant canapés service (Quince), oysters and caviar (The French Laundry), innovative fish courses that incorporate lesser used parts of the fish (Saison), Asian ingredients in desserts (Manresa), refined cooking techniques with vegetables (Ink), and a well thought out cocktail list (like the many great Chicago spots including Acadia and Blackbird).

Less than a half mile away on Sugar Creek Road and Tryon, the oldest school house in the county sits next to the Sugaw Creek Presbyterian church. The circa 1835 building, part of the congregation, served as a school until the 1900s, is where the sons of the plantation owner attended. The building is now a museum.
This humble structure served as a school for the boys from the plantation and continued to  educate students until the 1920s or 30s.
